      "writtenOn": "2019-11-17T19:27:20Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "i think buildbucket adopted stringification because inside queries it\u0027s less readable to write \"mode \u003d\u003d 1\".\n\nAlso, I never remember what integers default to in various systems: null or 0\nSo, when I have an integer-based enumeration in an API, so I think it\u0027s good idea to have any value intentionally to set to be !\u003d 0.",
      "revId": "09009084e5acabcc3762d5b6416d86150a7544fe",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "ea1c3a63_c89b0c72",
        "filename": "cq/api/bigquery/attempt.proto",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 18,
      "author": {
        "id": 1003190
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-11-21T22:30:27Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "It looks like by default enums will be treated like strings (when used as schemas for bq by bqschemaupdater etc.), e.g. for cr-buildbucket.builds.completed, status is an enum and in the table it\u0027s a string.\n\nAccording to https://cloud.google.com/apis/design/naming_convention, it\u0027s standard to have the 0 value of an enum be *_UNSPECIFIED. Now updated.",
      "parentUuid": "9eb2179e_2c7253a6",
      "revId": "09009084e5acabcc3762d5b6416d86150a7544fe",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
